steps.text:
Find the Overview by Summy AI Copilot section.

Click Generate overview if the overview has not been generated yet.

After generation, read the summary carefully. It may explain:

- current applicant status;
- document type affected by Forgery;
- reason why the document was considered suspicious;
- what the client needs to submit next.

Use this information as additional context before deciding whether reset is required.

Compare the third-party deposit amount with the current thresholds by payment system.

Current rules:

- Payabl — documents are not requested up to 1000 USD.

- Other payment systems — documents are not requested up to 3000 USD.

If the TPD amount is below the threshold:

- inform the client about the situation;

- direct the client to refund;

- warn the client not to use third-party payment details again;

- request KYC if needed.

If the TPD amount exceeds the threshold, request TPD documents before sending the client to refund.

For card deposits, request the following documents:

- Explanation of the reason for using third-party payment details;

- ID or passport of the third party;

- Current proof of address of the third party, not older than 6 months;

- Power of Attorney from the third party;

- Selfie of the third party holding ID/passport and Power of Attorney;

- Photo of the bank card.

The maximum timeframe during which the cardholder can initiate a chargeback is 540 days / 1.5 years.

If the third-party deposit is older than 540 days, TPD documents are not requested because the chargeback risk is considered expired.

In this case:

- inform the client about the violation;

- remind the client not to use third-party payment details again;

- do not request TPD documents.
